Besides the gas detectors installed inside the equipment, there are two H2 detector and one NH3 detector installed in the close to the container celling (since both gases are lighter than air). These three detectors are part of the SIS and are connected to the safety PLC. The H2 detectors are of different brands (Table 7
                           ) and measuring principle, which greatly reduces the common cause failures (CCF) (see Table 8
                           ). Table 5 summarizes all the gas detectors installed inside the container.

The SIS implements a number of safety instrumented functions (SIF), namely:

                                 -

SIF #1: disconnection of H2 supply and electricity supply to container, comprising the following sub-functions:

                                          #1a

disconnection of fuel cell H2 solenoid valve power supply (FV002, Fig. 11, D4 coord.);


                                          #1b

disconnection of electrolyzer power supply (-K.2.50 & -K.2.51, Fig. 11, E7 coord.);


                                          #1c

disconnection of all the electricity supplies in or toward the container: AC utility, PV, Li-ion battery, fuel cell;





                                 -

SIF #2: activation of the forced ventilation system in emergency mode (i.e. start of extractors #1 & #2), accompanied by a visual alarm;


                                 -

SIF #3: disconnection of all electricity power sources of the installation: conventional AC power and safety system AC power (in case of maintenance or fire hazard).

The inputs to the SIF are the following (from top to bottom on the left side of Fig. 14):

                                 •

H2 and NH3 detectors discussed in Sec. 4.6.1;


                                 •

a potential-free contact of the SCADA interface relay previously discussed in Sec. 4.5.5;


                                 •

an emergency button installed outside the container, on the front of CAB-2 cabinet (-S.2.02, Fig. 12);


                                 •

an emergency button installed inside the container, close to the door;


                                 •

an Extractors OK signal that indicates if the extractors are operational;


                                 •

a contact of the rotary switch that activates the air renewal mode of the force ventilation system.
